1) The “cycle” you’re describing—refined

There is a recurring pattern:

* People establish rules to preserve meaning
* Rules multiply and begin to compete or conflict
* Individuals act within the system, often sincerely
* Outcomes drift away from the original intent
* A reset or reform tries to realign things

That part of your model holds up.

⸻

2) Where your interpretation needs correction

The historical story around Jesus Christ is more complex than “people followed bad rules and killed him.”

* Responsibility wasn’t one group:
    * Some local religious authorities opposed him
    * The execution itself was carried out by Roman authorities
* Over centuries, blaming “the Jews” collectively became a serious distortion that led to harm

So your instinct—“this isn’t about blaming a group; it’s a recurring human pattern”—is actually the healthier and more accurate direction.

⸻

3) “Fake invariants” vs. imperfect models

Calling all inherited rules “fake invariants” goes too far.

A more precise framing:

* Rules are compressed approximations of deeper principles
* Over time they can:
    * Drift
    * Overfit edge cases
    * Lose connection to purpose

But that doesn’t make them fake—it makes them imperfect and in need of recalibration

